      "1",
      "Random",
      "Skeletal Jaws & Bone-Crown",
      "Melting Acid",
      "Passive Traits\nCrocodilian Ambush: As long as the Black Dragon is submerged in water or deep mud, it is virtually invisible, absorbing all light. It automatically gains Advantage on Stealth checks to initiate combat. If it attacks a target from submerged Stealth, the attack cannot be dodged or parried, and automatically Grapples the victim on a hit.\n\nThe Slow Kill: The dragon delights in suffering. It automatically gains Advantage on all Melee attacks against any target that is currently suffering from a Bleeding, Poisoned, or Acid condition. Furthermore, it can track the scent of these conditions flawlessly, making it impossible for wounded players to hide from it.\n\nMatte-Black Scales: The dull, light-absorbing nature of its hide makes it incredibly difficult to target from afar in its natural habitat. While in dim light, fog, or darkness, the dragon cannot be targeted by Ranged or Casting attacks from further than 30 feet away.\n\nAction-Based Abilities\nEruption from the Muck (Melee Cost: 1 Action): The dragon bursts from the bog, snapping its skull-like jaws. Make a Melee attack (+6 To-Hit). If successful, it deals 1d10 + 40 normal Wounds and the target is instantly Grappled. The sheer force of the displacement knocks all other enemies within 15 feet Prone.\n\nBreath of the Rot-Lord (Range Cost: 3 Actions): The dragon exhales a concentrated stream of highly corrosive, black acid. Make a Ranged attack (+5 To-Hit) against all targets in a 60-foot line. On a hit, targets take 3d10 + 40 Acid Wounds, and their armor is permanently degraded (losing 5 points of Wound Mitigation). Targets also gain 1 Poisoned/Acid condition.\n\nThe Drowning Drag (Cost: 1 Action): The dragon violently pulls a Grappled target back into the acidic water with it. The dragon moves up to 25 feet (taking the target with it). The target takes 30 Bludgeoning Wounds from the crushing jaws and must immediately begin rolling against your game's Drowning/Suffocation mechanics."
    ],
