      "Rusted Iron Morningstar, Throwing Javelins",
      "1H or 2H Iron MorningStar",
      "Hurled Javelin",
      "Passive Traits \nSilent Contortionist: The Bugbear's loose joints and padded feet make it a master infiltrator. It automatically gains Advantage on all Stealth checks. Furthermore, it can squeeze through windows, grates, or gaps designed for Small creatures without suffering any Movement penalties.\n\nGangly Reach: Its unnaturally long arms allow it to strike from completely unexpected angles. The Bugbear's Melee attacks have a 10-foot reach, allowing it to attack players from behind cover, around corners, or while hanging from the rafters without engaging in base-to-base contact.\n\nBrutal Efficiency (The Bully's Advantage): The Bugbear wants to end the fight in the first three seconds. If the Bugbear attacks a target that has not yet taken a turn in combat, or attacks a target from Stealth, its Melee attacks automatically deal double Wounds.\n\nAction-Based Abilities \nShadow-Stalker's Drop (Melee Cost: 2 Actions): The Bugbear drops from the ceiling or bursts from a thicket to deliver a devastating opening strike. It moves up to 15 feet and makes a Melee attack (+3 To-Hit). If successful, it deals 1d10 + 25 Wounds, and the target must pass a Physique(9) test or instantly gain 1 Stunned condition from the concussive trauma.\n\nMorningstar Sweep (Melee Cost: 1 Action): Utilizing its 10-foot reach, the Bugbear swings its morningstar at the party's legs. Make a Melee attack (+3 To-Hit). If successful, it deals half Wounds 1d10 + 8, but the target is violently tripped and knocked Prone.\n\nFade into the Dark (Cost: 1 Action): The Bugbear refuses to fight a fair battle. It instantly Disengages from melee combat without triggering any free attacks of opportunity and can move up to 20 feet into a shadowed area, cover, or up a wall to re-enter Stealth."
    ],
