      "4-12",
      "usted Shiv, Pouch of Blinding Spores, Soot-Stained Rags",
      "Rusted Shiv",
      "Pocket Spores, Throwing Dagger",
      "Passive Traits\nChasm Vermin: The Gutter-Blades are entirely at home in the pitch black. They ignore all penalties for dim light or darkness. Furthermore, if a Gutter-Blade makes a Melee attack against a target that is already engaged with at least two other allied Gutter-Blades, they automatically gain Advantage on the To-Hit roll (Pack Tactics).\n\nCraven Flight: Their instinct is self-preservation above all else. If a Gutter-Blade takes any Wounds, or if they witness an allied Dark Elf die within 15 feet of them, they immediately use a Reaction to Disengage and move 15 feet away, scurrying up the nearest wall if possible.\n\nCrude Toxin: They don't have access to refined neurotoxins, so they smear their shivs with whatever venomous centipede ichor they can find. Any time a Gutter-Blade scores a Critical Hit with a Melee attack, the crude venom seeps in, applying 1 Poisoned condition to the target.\n\nAction-Based Abilities\nGut-Stab (Melee Cost: 1 Action): A desperate, upward thrust with a rusty blade. Make a Melee attack (+2 To-Hit). If successful, it deals 1d10 +6 Piercing Wounds.\n\nPocket Spores (Range Cost: 1 Action): The Elf reaches into their rags and hurls a handful of bioluminescent fungal spores at a target's face. Make a Ranged attack against a target within 10 feet. On a hit, it deals no Wounds, but the target is Blinded for 1 round as the glowing powder burns their eyes.\n\nScurry (Cost: 1 Action): The Gutter-Blade drops to all fours, moving up to 30 feet. During this movement, they can climb vertical surfaces or hang from ceilings at their full movement speed without needing to make Agility tests."
    ],
