      "Clumsy Debris Slam",
      "None",
      "Passive Traits\nAmorphous Clod: Because it is just a held-together pile of dirt, it doesn't have vital organs. The Rubble-Clod is completely immune to the Bleeding condition and takes no extra Wounds from Critical Hits (the attacker merely knocks away a harmless chunk of stone).\n\nMud-Tether: Its dragging, muddy form ruins the terrain. Any space the Rubble-Clod currently occupies, or has walked through on its previous turn, is automatically considered Difficult Terrain for any non-Earth elementals.\n\nClumsy Mass: Due to its -1 Agility, it automatically fails any test to avoid being knocked Prone. However, because it has no true anatomy, standing back up from Prone costs it 0 Actions (it simply shifts its center of mass).\n\nAction-Based Abilities\nDebris Slam (Melee Cost: 1 Action): The creature simply falls forward or swings a heavy clump of roots. Make a Melee attack (+2 To-Hit). If successful, it deals 1d10 + 10 Bludgeoning Wounds.\n\nFling Mud (Range Cost: 1 Action): The elemental tears off a piece of its own body and hurls it. Make a Ranged attack (+1 To-Hit) against a target within 20 feet. On a hit, it deals 1d10 +5 Wounds and the target is Blinded until they spend an Action to wipe the thick mud from their eyes.\n\nSinkhole (Cost: 2 Actions): The Rubble-Clod violently collapses its own form to trap an enemy. It targets an adjacent enemy. That enemy must pass an Agility(4) test or become Grappled and Restrained as the elemental turns into a localized pit of quicksand around their legs. The elemental cannot use Debris Slam while maintaining this grapple."
