      "5-50",
      "crap-Plate, Jagged Filth-Shank, 1d3 Boom-Pots",
      "Jagged Filth-Shank",
      "Boom-Pot",
      "Passive Traits\nStrength in the Shadows: A Night-Cutter fights dirty. They automatically gain Advantage on all To-Hit rolls as long as there is at least one conscious allied Goblin adjacent to their target.\n\nTwitching Ears: Their massive ears act like radar. Night-Cutters are completely immune to the Surprised condition and cannot be flanked by conventional stealth.\n\nCoward’s Retreat: If a Night-Cutter takes damage that drops its Health below 50% (6 Wounds or less), it immediately uses a free Reaction to Disengage (preventing attacks of opportunity) and moves its full 18 Movement speed directly away from the source of the damage, screaming for help.\n\nAction-Based Abilities\nFilth-Shank (Melee Cost: 1 Action): The goblin violently stabs at an enemy's exposed joints. Make a Melee attack (+1 To-Hit). If successful, it deals 1d10 + 6 Piercing Wounds, and the target must pass a Physique(6) test or gain 1 Poisoned condition from the rusty, feces-coated blade.\n\nBoom-Pot Lob (Range Cost: 2 Actions): The goblin lights the fuse on an unstable alchemical sludge-pot and hurls it. Make a Ranged attack (+2 To-Hit) targeting a specific square up to 30 feet away. The pot explodes in a 10-foot radius. All creatures in the blast zone must pass an Agility(6) test or take 15 Fire/Acid Wounds. (Note: Goblins do not care about friendly fire and will happily catch their allies in the blast).\n\nScuttle & Hide (Cost: 1 Action): The goblin leverages its tiny size. It may move up to 15 feet and immediately gain Total Concealment if it ends its movement behind cover or in dim light."
