      "",
      "3-15",
      "Leather, shield",
      "dagger, short sword",
      "Sling",
      "Passive Traits\nSupernatural Luck: The Halfling is favored by fate. If an enemy lands a Critical Hit against the Halfling, the Halfling can spend 1 Luck point (out of their pool of 4) to force the enemy to reroll the attack completely. Additionally, they automatically pass the first Agility test they are forced to make in any combat encounter.\n\nSilent Grace: The Slip-Step moves without making a sound. They permanently possess Advantage on all Stealth checks, and they completely ignore Movement penalties from natural Difficult Terrain (like mud, underbrush, or loose scree).\n\nUnderfoot Evasion: A Halfling knows how to fight giants. They gain a +2 bonus to their Defense (bringing it to an effective 7) against any Melee attack made by a creature of Large size or greater, easily ducking under the sweeping, clumsy blows.\n\nAction-Based Abilities\nAchilles Strike (Cost: 1 Action): The Halfling targets the vulnerable joints of a larger foe. Make a Melee attack (+2 To-Hit). If successful, it deals 51d10 + 5 Piercing Wounds, and the target's Movement is reduced by half on their next turn as their knee or ankle buckles.\n\nDistracting Ricochet (Range Cost: 1 Action): The Halfling fires a sling bullet with impossible geometry. Make a Ranged attack (+2 To-Hit) against a target up to 40 feet away. On a hit, it deals 1d10 + 12 Bludgeoning Wounds. Whether it hits or misses, the bullet ricochets, granting the next allied attack against that target Advantage.\n\nVanish into the Leaves (Cost: 1 Action): The Halfling utilizes their size and earth-toned clothing. They may move up to 15 feet and instantly gain the Concealed condition, making it impossible to target them with Ranged attacks or Spells until they reveal themselves or move into the open."
    ],
