      "5-50",
      "Crude Shiv, Sling, Caltrops, Pouch of Trap Mechanisms",
      "Crude Shiv",
      "Sling or throwing dagger",
      "Passive Traits\nWarren Crawler: The Kobold treats all difficult terrain in subterranean environments as normal terrain. Furthermore, they can squeeze through tiny crevices and gaps that Medium or larger creatures cannot enter.\n\nSafety in Numbers: The Kobold is a coward at heart. If an allied Kobold is killed within 15 feet of it, it must pass a Willpower test (which it will likely fail with a 2) or immediately use its next turn to flee. However, while outnumbering an enemy at least 2-to-1 in melee, it gains Advantage and +1 To-Hit on all attack rolls.\n\nTrapmaster's Step: Kobolds are perfectly attuned to their own warrens. They are completely immune to triggering their own traps and automatically succeed on checks made to spot traps set by others.\n\nAction-Based Abilities\nScurry and Shank (Melee Cost: 1 Action): The Kobold darts forward, stabs, and immediately retreats. Make a Melee attack (+1 To-Hit). If successful, it deals 1d10 + 4 Piercing Wounds, and the Kobold may instantly move up to 10 feet away without triggering a defensive counter-attack.\n\nSling-Stone (Range Cost: 1 Action): The Kobold hurls a jagged rock from a safe distance. Make a Ranged attack (+3 To-Hit) up to 40 feet. On a hit, it deals 1d10 + 6 Bludgeoning Wounds.\n\nSpring the Trap! (Cost: 2 Actions): The Kobold pulls a hidden lever, cuts a tripwire, or drops a rigged payload on an area within 30 feet. All enemies within a 10-foot radius of the target zone must pass an Agility(6) test or take 15 Bludgeoning/Piercing Wounds from falling rocks or spiked logs."
    ],
