      "Knotted Wooden Fists",
      "Hurled Debris/Hardened Sap/Rocks",
      "Passive Traits\nFalse Canopy: When the Lesser Treant remains motionless, it is entirely indistinguishable from a normal tree. It automatically gains Advantage on any check made to ambush or surprise intruders who enter its grove.\n\nIron Bark: The dense wood of the Treant turns away glancing blows. It is highly resistant to Piercing damage (arrows, spears), taking half damage from these sources. However, it possesses a severe vulnerability to Fire, taking double damage from all flame-based attacks.\n\nDeep Roots: While standing on natural earth, soil, or grass, the Treant cannot be physically pushed, dragged, or knocked Prone by any creature of Size Large or smaller.\n\nAction-Based Abilities\nTimber Sweep (Melee Cost: 1 Action): The Treant swings a heavy, knotted branch. Make a Melee attack (+2 To-Hit). If successful, it deals 1d10 + 15 Bludgeoning Wounds and pushes the target 5 feet backward.\n\nEntangling Roots (Cost: 2 Actions): The Treant plunges its hands into the soil, causing roots to violently erupt beneath a target within 20 feet. The target must pass an Agility(7) test or gain the Grappled and Restrained conditions as the roots bind their legs to the earth.\n\nSticky Sap (Cost: 1 Action): The Treant hurls a glob of hardened, incredibly sticky sap at a nearby enemy. Make a Ranged attack (+1 To-Hit) up to 25 feet. On a hit, the target takes no Wounds, but their weapon or boots become coated, inflicting the Slowed condition until they use an Action to pry the sap off."
