      "Ancient Recurve Bow, Quiver of Barbed Arrows",
      "Serpent Hair / Constricting Tail",
      "Shortbow",
      "Passive Traits\nAura of Stone: The air around the Medusa feels cold and heavy. Enemies beginning their turn within 30 feet of her suffer a -1 penalty to their Agility characteristic as their joints stiffen.\n\nSlithering Evasion: The Medusa's serpentine lower half allows her to move with unnatural fluidity. She ignores movement penalties in swamps, ruins, and sandy terrain, and her erratic movements grant a +2 bonus to her Defense against ranged attacks.\n\nToxic Blood: Her veins run with pure venom. She is completely immune to the Poison and Disease conditions. Any creature that scores an unmodified 10 on a melee attack against her takes a splash of acidic blood, suffering D10 wounds.\n\nThe Petrifying Gaze (Aura): If a creature starts its turn within 40 feet of the Medusa and is not actively averting its eyes (fighting blind), it must pass a Willpower test against her staggering 15 Charisma. On a failure, the creature gains the Paralyzed condition as their skin begins to calcify. If they fail this check twice in a single encounter, they are permanently turned to stone.\n\nAction-Based Abilities\nVenomous Viper Strike (Melee - Cost: 1 Action): The serpents writhing upon her head lash out with blinding speed. This 1-Handed attack, dealing a quick 1d10 +10 wounds. The victim must pass a Physique(10) test or immediately suffer 1 Poison condition.\n\nSerpentine Shortbow (Range - Cost: 1 Action): Drawing a sleek, bone-carved bow, she fires a jagged, black-fletched arrow. Relying on her high Agility, (+4 To-Hit) this ranged attack deals 1d10 + 20 piercing wounds. This jagged arrow head is drenched in her blood, is struck make a Physique(11) test or suffer additonal 2d10 poison wounds.\n\nViper's Coil (melee Cost: 2 Actions): The Medusa lunges with her massive tail to crush an enemy. Make a Melee attack (+4 To-Hit). On a hit, it deals 1d10 + 20 Bludgeoning Wounds and the target is Grappled and Restrained. While restrained this way, the target is forced to look at her, automatically triggering her Petrifying Gaze trait on her next turn."
