      "Massive Claws & Fangs",
      "None",
      "Passive Traits\nGhost of the Taiga: The tiger's striped coat and padded paws make it the ultimate forest stalker. It gains automatic Advantage on all Stealth tests in forested, snowy, or tall-grass environments. Additionally, its natural \"snowshoe\" paws allow it to completely ignore movement penalties from deep snow, ice, or uneven woodland terrain.\n\nArmor-Shearing Claws: The tiger's claws are thick, razor-sharp, and backed by immense weight. Any melee attack made by the Tiger automatically ignores the first 5 points of a target's Armor Wound Mitigation, treating chainmail and leather as if it were bare flesh.\n\nPredator's Momentum: If the Tiger moves at least 20 feet in a straight line toward a target before making a melee attack, the sheer kinetic force of its mass grants it Advantage on the To-Hit roll, and a successful hit automatically knocks the target Prone, if large size or smaller.\n\nAction-Based Abilities\nThunderous Roar (Cost: 2 Actions): The Tiger unleashes a primal, bone-rattling roar. All enemies within a 40-foot radius must pass a severe Willpower(7) test. On a failure, the sheer terror of the sound paralyzes them, inflicting 1 Stunned condition and causing them to drop whatever they are currently holding in their hands.\n\nThe Ghost's Blur (Melee Cost: 1 Action): The Tiger lashes out with a lightning-fast swipe of its massive paws. Make a Melee attack (+6 To-Hit). If successful, it deals normal 1d10 + 25 melee Wounds and instantly inflicts 1 Bleeding condition. The Tiger can then immediately move up to 15 feet away without triggering any free attacks from the engaged target.\n\nJugular Crush (Melee Cost: 2 Actions): The Tiger's signature killing blow, used only when its prey is vulnerable. This action can only be used against a target that is currently Prone or Stunned. Make a Melee attack (+4 To-Hit). If successful, it deals 3d10 + 25 Wounds. If this attack reduces the target to 0 Wounds, the Tiger instantly regains 1 Action as it seamlessly pivots to its next victim."
    ],
